    oneSentenceSummary: "BYU is the largest faith-based university in America and the most deliberately structured — a Latter-day Saint institution where the Honor Code, mission service, and religious formation are inseparable from academic preparation, producing graduates with language skills in 50+ languages, global mission networks, and a 400,000-person alumni community bound by shared values and extraordinary professional loyalty.",

    pipeline: "67% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #80 nationally (US News 2025). 34,000+ undergraduates — one of the largest private university enrollments in America. The Marriott School of Business is top-20 nationally in accounting and supply chain — arguably the best-value elite business program in America at BYU's tuition rate. The Ira A. Fulton College of Engineering is top-40. The J. Reuben Clark Law School is top-35. BYU's accounting program has produced more Big Four partners and more licensed CPAs per capita than almost any other program in America. Goldman Sachs, McKinsey, Deloitte, EY, and every major professional firm maintain active BYU recruiting pipelines. Tuition is dramatically subsidized for LDS members — approximately $6,000/year for LDS students, making BYU the most affordable elite education in America for qualifying students.",

    hiddenPathway: "The returned missionary advantage is BYU's most distinctive and most globally powerful career asset. Most BYU students serve 18-24 month missions before or during their undergraduate years, living in a foreign country and becoming functionally fluent in a foreign language. BYU graduates hold the highest concentration of foreign language proficiency of any large university in America — Portuguese, Mandarin, Spanish, Japanese, Korean, Arabic, Russian — and this proficiency is genuine, mission-earned, and professionally deployable. Global consulting firms, international banks, US intelligence agencies, and multinational corporations recruit BYU graduates specifically for this language capability and international experience. The BYU Management Society — a global professional network of LDS business professionals — operates chapters in 100+ cities and functions as one of the most active university professional networks in the world.",

    institutionalSecret: "BYU's Honor Code is not window dressing — it is the operating system of the institution. The code requires students to abstain from alcohol, tobacco, coffee, and tea; to dress modestly; to maintain sexual chastity; and to live by standards consistent with LDS religious teaching. This creates a student body that is demographically unusual: older than average (due to mission service), unusually sober, and characterized by a discipline and work ethic that employers consistently note in BYU graduates. The campus social culture — dating culture in particular — reflects LDS norms around marriage and family that are distinct from peer universities. Understanding BYU requires understanding that the Honor Code is not a restriction students tolerate but a set of values they have chosen.",

