    archetype: "The Engineering and Computing Powerhouse — The Public University That Invented Modern Computer Science",

    oneSentenceSummary: "Illinois is the public university that built ARPANET, invented the Mosaic web browser, and produced more Fortune 500 CEOs than any other public university in America — a top-5 engineering and CS program embedded in Champaign-Urbana with a Chicago and Silicon Valley recruiting ecosystem that delivers private-university outcomes at public-university scale.",

    pipeline: "44% acceptance rate overall; Grainger College of Engineering and CS programs are significantly more selective. #12 among public universities nationally (US News 2025). 34,000 undergraduates. The Grainger College of Engineering is top-5 nationally in CS, electrical, civil, and mechanical engineering. The Gies College of Business is top-20 nationally with the iMBA among the most innovative online business programs in America. The School of Information Sciences is top-5 nationally. Google, Amazon, Microsoft, Apple, Meta, and every major technology company maintain dedicated Illinois CS recruiting pipelines. Illinois graduates hold senior engineering and product leadership roles at virtually every major technology company. 500,000+ living alumni with exceptional loyalty and Chicago corporate corridor concentration.",

    hiddenPathway: "Illinois's most undersurfaced advantage is the CS + X degree programs — Computer Science + Astronomy, CS + Economics, CS + Statistics, CS + Linguistics, CS + Philosophy — that allow students to combine the most recruited technical degree in America with substantive depth in another discipline. These dual-degree tracks produce graduates who can code and think across domains — a combination that quantitative finance, data science, AI policy, and computational social science firms recruit specifically. The Illinois Research Park — a 250,000 square foot innovation hub adjacent to campus — houses 90+ companies including Caterpillar, State Farm, and startups spun out of Illinois research. The Siebel Center for Design and the Entrepreneurship programs are creating a startup ecosystem that is beginning to rival larger-city peers.",

    institutionalSecret: "Illinois's geographic location — in flat central Illinois, 130 miles south of Chicago — creates a campus insularity that is the engine of its community cohesion. Champaign-Urbana has a genuine college town identity: the bars of Green Street, the Assembly Hall concerts, the Fighting Illini football and basketball culture. Illinois students who embrace the campus community describe an intensity of shared experience that urban universities cannot produce. The Chicago alumni network — the most active Illinois alumni chapter in the world — activates immediately upon graduation: Illinois graduates in Chicago hire Illinois graduates at rates that create a self-reinforcing professional ecosystem in the city.",

    theRoom: "Champaign-Urbana, Illinois — twin cities of 130,000 set in the flat agricultural heart of Illinois. The campus is sprawling: the Main Quad, the Alma Mater statue, the Morrow Plots (the oldest experimental agricultural field in America), and 647 acres of red brick and limestone architecture. Chicago is 130 miles north — 2.5 hours by car, 2.5 hours by Amtrak. The insularity of the location is real and is also the source of the campus community strength.",

    lifestyle: "Big Ten culture with engineering dominance. Football Saturdays at Memorial Stadium and basketball at the State Farm Center are major social events. Greek life is active — approximately 20% participation. The Green Street bar and restaurant corridor is the social spine. The campus culture reflects the engineering and CS student body: hardworking, collaborative, and pragmatic about professional outcomes from year one.",

