    oneSentenceSummary: "Penn is the Ivy League university most explicitly oriented toward professional achievement and wealth creation — home to Wharton, the most famous undergraduate business program in the world, in a city that is simultaneously a major financial center, a leading medical research hub, and a startup ecosystem in ascent.",

    pipeline: "5.8% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #6 nationally (US News 2025). 10,000 undergraduates across four undergraduate schools: Wharton School (business), College of Arts and Sciences, School of Engineering and Applied Science, and School of Nursing. Wharton's undergraduate program is the most selective and most recognized undergraduate business degree in the world — Goldman Sachs, Blackstone, KKR, and every major Wall Street firm have dedicated Wharton recruiting pipelines. Penn Medicine is one of the top academic medical systems in America. Penn Law is top-10. The Perelman School of Medicine is top-5. 330,000+ living alumni with extraordinary concentration in finance, consulting, medicine, and law.",

    hiddenPathway: "Penn's coordinated dual-degree programs are among the most powerful and least publicized features of the undergraduate experience. The Huntsman Program (international studies and business), the Jerome Fisher Program in Management and Technology (M&T — Wharton + Engineering), the Roy and Diana Vagelos Program in Life Sciences and Management (Wharton + pre-med), and the Rajendra and Neera Singh Program in Networked and Social Systems Engineering (NETS) are coordinated dual-degree tracks that produce graduates with credentials no single-school program can match. M&T graduates — who complete both Wharton and Engineering — are among the most recruited undergraduates in America. Penn's startup ecosystem within Pennovation Works is producing early-stage companies at a rate that is reshaping Penn's traditional finance-dominant professional identity.",

    institutionalSecret: "Penn's social culture is more Greek-dominated than any other Ivy — approximately 30% of Penn undergraduates participate in Greek life, and the fraternity and sorority social system is the dominant organizing architecture of the social experience. This is a defining feature of Penn's social life that many applicants don't fully understand before arriving. Locust Walk — the central pedestrian spine of campus — is where social, intellectual, and professional life converges daily. Penn also has one of the strongest alumni donor cultures in the Ivy League — Penn alumni give at rates that fund some of the most generous scholarship programs in the university's history.",

    theRoom: "West Philadelphia, Pennsylvania — 2.5 miles from Center City Philadelphia. The campus is a contained, tree-lined residential neighborhood within a major American city. Philadelphia is underrated as a city for university students: world-class art museums, restaurant culture, a growing tech and biotech sector, and cost of living dramatically lower than New York. New York is 90 minutes on Amtrak. The Penn campus is physically beautiful, with Locust Walk as its social spine and Houston Hall as its communal center.",

    lifestyle: "Ambitious, social, and professionally oriented from the first week. Wharton culture permeates the whole campus — even students in the College feel the gravitational pull of professional networking, recruiting timelines, and career preparation. Greek life is central. The Penn social scene is active, well-funded, and Philadelphia-adjacent. The Quad — Penn's freshman residential complex — is one of the most social freshman experiences in the Ivy League.",

    bestFitPersonality: "Pre-professionally oriented, finance or consulting or medicine career ambition, socially active, network-motivated, comfortable with competitive professional culture, high Conscientiousness and Extraversion",

