    archetype: "The Open Curriculum University — Intellectual Freedom, Creative Ambition, and the Self-Directed Life",

    oneSentenceSummary: "Brown is the Ivy League university built around a radical premise — that students learn best when they choose what to learn — and the Open Curriculum, combined with Providence's creative energy and Brown's unusually warm social culture, produces graduates who are among the most intellectually self-possessed and creatively ambitious in American higher education.",

    pipeline: "5.6% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #9 nationally (US News 2025). 7,500 undergraduates in Brown College. The Open Curriculum — no required courses, no distribution requirements, complete freedom to design one's own education — is the defining structural feature. Students take courses Satisfactory/No Credit as a default option, reducing the grade anxiety that characterizes peer institutions. Brown's programs in cognitive neuroscience, literary arts, international relations, public health, and computer science are among the strongest at any undergraduate institution. Warren Alpert Medical School is top-30. The Providence startup and creative economy is increasingly drawing Brown graduates who stay.",

    hiddenPathway: "The Pembroke Center for Teaching and Research on Women, the Watson Institute for International and Public Affairs, and the Data Science Institute are among the most active interdisciplinary research hubs at any undergraduate-focused Ivy. The Brown-RISD dual degree (BRDD) — a five-year program producing graduates with both a Brown AB and a RISD BFA — is one of the most distinctive and most sought-after undergraduate credentials in America: the only program that trains students simultaneously as rigorous liberal arts scholars and professional artists or designers. The entrepreneurship ecosystem at Brown — through the Nelson Center for Entrepreneurship — is producing startups at a rate that is transforming Brown's traditional arts and humanities identity into something more entrepreneurially diverse.",

    institutionalSecret: "Brown's S/NC grading option is more significant than it first appears. Students can take any course Satisfactory/No Credit without it affecting their GPA. This structural choice changes the intellectual risk calculus — Brown students take courses in subjects they know nothing about, with faculty they've only heard of, without fear of grade consequences. The result is a breadth of intellectual formation that grade-anxious environments cannot produce. Brown students routinely describe taking courses in subjects they never intended to study and discovering the direction of their careers.",

    theRoom: "College Hill, Providence, Rhode Island — on a hill above downtown Providence, overlooking the Rhode Island State House. Providence is a mid-size New England city with extraordinary restaurant culture (the highest restaurant-per-capita ratio of any city in America), a vibrant arts scene driven partly by RISD and Brown, and a cost of living dramatically lower than Boston or New York. Boston is 50 minutes on the Amtrak Acela. New York is 3 hours. The Brown-RISD campus overlap gives College Hill a creative energy that is unusual for an Ivy League environment.",

