    pipeline: "78% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #96 nationally (US News 2025). 15,000 undergraduates. The LeBow College of Business is top-75 nationally. The College of Engineering is top-40 in electrical, mechanical, and civil engineering. The Antoinette Westphal College of Media Arts and Design is one of the most industry-connected design and media programs in the Mid-Atlantic. Drexel's co-op partners include Comcast (Philadelphia HQ), GlaxoSmithKline, Johnson & Johnson, SEPTA, and hundreds of Philadelphia-area employers who have built Drexel co-op recruitment into their talent pipeline. Drexel's employment rate at graduation consistently ranks among the highest in the country — over 95% employed or enrolled within 6 months.",

    hiddenPathway: "Drexel's co-op program is not an optional internship enhancement — it is the structural architecture of the degree. Every Drexel undergraduate completes three 6-month co-op rotations, typically in their third, fourth, and fifth years, with full-time paid professional positions averaging $19-$22/hour. Students graduate with a five-year degree, three employer references, a professional network, and demonstrated professional competency that traditional four-year graduates cannot claim. The Drexel START (Startups at Drexel) accelerator and the Baiada Institute for Entrepreneurship give students who want to found rather than join a structured startup pathway. The College of Nursing and Health Professions — partnered with Hahnemann University Hospital and the Philadelphia healthcare corridor — is one of the most clinically integrated nursing programs in the Northeast.",

    institutionalSecret: "Comcast is Drexel's most important corporate relationship — and it is a relationship that goes far beyond recruiting. Comcast NBCUniversal, headquartered in the Comcast Center three blocks from campus, employs hundreds of Drexel co-op students annually across technology, media, business, and engineering. The relationship is bidirectional: Comcast helps fund Drexel programs, Drexel produces Comcast's technology and operations talent pipeline. For students interested in media technology, cable and broadband infrastructure, streaming technology, or entertainment business, the Drexel-Comcast corridor is a unique career development pathway that no other university can replicate.",

    theRoom: "University City, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania — the Drexel campus sits in University City, the academic and medical research district of West Philadelphia immediately adjacent to Penn and the University of Pennsylvania Medical Center. Market Street is the commercial spine. 30th Street Station — Amtrak's Philadelphia hub — is two blocks from campus. Center City Philadelphia is a 10-minute walk across the Schuylkill River. The Philadelphia food, arts, and cultural scene is accessible and genuinely excellent. The proximity to Penn creates an academic ecosystem that Drexel students benefit from through shared resources and social overlap.",

    lifestyle: "Professionally oriented from year one. The co-op calendar creates a social architecture where roughly one-third of students are always on co-op rotation — off campus, working full-time — which gives the campus a different social rhythm than traditional universities. Greek life is present but secondary to co-op culture. The Philadelphia social scene — South Street, Rittenhouse Square, the Reading Terminal Market, Eagles and Phillies games — extends undergraduate life into the city.",

    bestFitPersonality: "Career-ready and work-experience motivated, engineering or business or design career track, comfortable with five-year timeline, Philadelphia lifestyle oriented, values employer relationships over campus insularity, high Conscientiousness",

