    archetype: "The Philadelphia Opportunity Engine — Access, Professional Mobility, and the Most Diverse Major University in Pennsylvania",

    oneSentenceSummary: "Temple is the university that gives Philadelphia to students who couldn't afford Penn or Drexel — a 40,000-student public research university in the heart of North Philadelphia whose Fox School of Business, Klein College of Media, and Tyler School of Art produce graduates embedded in Philadelphia's professional ecosystem at a price point that makes the city's career opportunities genuinely accessible.",

    pipeline: "73% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #121 nationally (US News 2025). 28,000 undergraduates. The Fox School of Business is top-50 nationally and the largest business school in the Philadelphia region — accounting, finance, risk management, and actuarial science programs recruit from every major Philadelphia employer. The Klein College of Media and Communication produces broadcast journalists, public relations professionals, and digital media producers for every major Philadelphia and national media outlet. Temple Law is top-75. Temple's Lewis Katz School of Medicine is top-75 in research. Deloitte, KPMG, Comcast, Aramark, Lincoln Financial, and every major Philadelphia corporation recruit Temple at volume. 350,000+ living alumni — one of the largest networks in Pennsylvania.",

    hiddenPathway: "Temple's most distinctive structural advantage is its location — the Main Campus in North Philadelphia, the Ambler Campus in suburban Montgomery County, the Center City Campus at 1515 Market Street, and Temple Japan in Tokyo create a multi-campus ecosystem that gives students geographic flexibility within a single university. The Center City Campus is particularly valuable: it places working professionals and traditional students in the same classrooms 2 miles from Philadelphia's corporate center, creating networking opportunities that campus-only universities cannot provide. The Diamond Gold Scholars program and the Fly in 4 tuition guarantee — Temple guarantees four-year graduation or pays for additional semesters — reflect an institutional commitment to student success that is unusual at a university of Temple's size.",

    institutionalSecret: "Temple's alumni density in Philadelphia is its most underappreciated career asset. In Philadelphia professional settings — accounting firms, law firms, hospitals, media companies, corporate offices — Temple alumni are the most prevalent university cohort. The concentration of 350,000 Temple graduates in the Philadelphia metro creates a referral culture that is quieter than Penn's but more geographically concentrated. The Owl network in Philadelphia operates on the premise that Temple graduates help Temple graduates — particularly in law, accounting, healthcare, and media — and the density makes it structurally effective.",

    theRoom: "North Philadelphia and Center City, Pennsylvania — the Main Campus occupies 118 acres in North Philadelphia, one of the most economically complex urban neighborhoods in America. The SEPTA Broad Street Line (the Broad Street Subway) runs directly through campus, connecting it to Center City in 20 minutes and South Philadelphia in 10. The campus has undergone significant physical transformation: the SERC (Science Education and Research Center), the Student Center, and the Morgan Hall expansion have created a modern academic core. The proximity to Jefferson Hospital, Temple Hospital, and the Fox Chase Cancer Center creates a healthcare research ecosystem accessible by public transit.",

    lifestyle: "Urban, diverse, and professionally practical. Temple's student body reflects Philadelphia's demographics more accurately than any peer institution. Greek life is present but secondary to city life. Owl athletics — particularly basketball and football in the American Athletic Conference — provide campus culture anchors. The Philadelphia social scene is the primary social backdrop: the Italian Market, Reading Terminal Market, South Street, the museums, and SEPTA's accessibility make Philadelphia genuinely navigable without a car.",

