    oneSentenceSummary: "Rutgers is the most strategically underrated public university in America — located 33 miles from Midtown Manhattan in the pharmaceutical capital of the world, with a research enterprise that rivals flagship universities twice its national ranking, producing the most diverse graduating class of any major research university in the country.",

    pipeline: "66% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #57 among public universities nationally (US News 2025). 36,000 undergraduates across New Brunswick, Newark, and Camden. The Rutgers Business School is top-40 nationally in supply chain and finance. The Ernest Mario School of Pharmacy is top-20 nationally — New Jersey is home to Johnson & Johnson, Merck, Pfizer, Bristol-Myers Squibb, Sanofi, and virtually every major pharmaceutical company in the world, and Rutgers is the primary talent pipeline. The School of Communication and Information is top-15. New York-based financial firms (Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan, Citigroup), consulting firms (Deloitte, McKinsey), and pharmaceutical companies all maintain active Rutgers recruiting pipelines. 500,000+ living alumni — one of the largest networks in the country.",

    hiddenPathway: "New Jersey's pharmaceutical corridor is Rutgers's most powerful and least publicized career pipeline. The concentration of pharmaceutical and biotech companies within 30 miles of the New Brunswick campus is unmatched anywhere in the world: Johnson & Johnson (New Brunswick headquarters), Merck (Rahway), Pfizer (Pearl River NY, 30 miles), Bristol-Myers Squibb (Princeton), Sanofi (Bridgewater), and hundreds of biotech firms in the Princeton-New Brunswick corridor recruit Rutgers pharmacy, chemistry, biology, and business graduates as a primary talent source. The Rutgers-Robert Wood Johnson Medical School creates a direct clinical and research pipeline into RWJUH, one of the top-10 hospitals in New Jersey. The Honors College at Rutgers — the Byrne Seminars, the living-learning communities, the Honors faculty — delivers honors program intimacy to students who engage it.",

    institutionalSecret: "Rutgers's most counterintuitive advantage is its New York City proximity combined with New Jersey cost of living. Students can intern in Midtown Manhattan while paying New Jersey public university tuition and living in New Brunswick — a combination of geographic access and economic value that no peer institution in the region can match. The New York alumni network — concentrated in finance, media, pharmaceutical, and consulting — is the largest and most active Rutgers alumni community, and it activates for Rutgers graduates who proactively engage it. The Rutgers identity in New York professional settings is not Harvard's prestige — it is a different signal: serious, economically aware, and from New Jersey, which in New York is a compliment.",

    theRoom: "New Brunswick, New Jersey — a mid-size city of 56,000 on the Raritan River, 33 miles southwest of Midtown Manhattan on the Northeast Corridor rail line. The Rutgers campus is distributed across multiple areas of New Brunswick — College Avenue, Busch, Livingston, and Cook-Douglass — creating a multi-campus character that is simultaneously New Jersey and immediately adjacent to one of the most economically significant metros in the world. The train to New York Penn Station takes 55 minutes.",

