    oneSentenceSummary: "Virginia Tech is the engineering and applied science flagship of Virginia — a top-25 engineering program whose Hokies alumni network rivals Notre Dame in loyalty intensity, whose co-op and research programs place graduates into defense, aerospace, cybersecurity, and technology careers at rates that consistently outperform the university's national ranking, embedded in Blacksburg — one of the most beautiful and most insular college towns in America.",

    pipeline: "57% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #68 nationally (US News 2025). 28,000 undergraduates. The College of Engineering is top-25 nationally in aerospace, civil, electrical, and computer engineering. The Pamplin College of Business is top-50. The College of Architecture and Urban Studies is top-20. Northrop Grumman, Raytheon, Lockheed Martin, Boeing, Leidos, and every major defense contractor maintain active Virginia Tech recruiting pipelines. Amazon, Microsoft, Google, and Capital One — all with significant Northern Virginia operations — recruit Hokie engineers and computer scientists at volume. The Virginia Tech Research Division generates over $600M annually in sponsored research, with particular strength in defense, cybersecurity, and agricultural systems. 260,000+ living alumni with exceptional Virginia and national loyalty.",

    hiddenPathway: "Virginia Tech's National Capital Region campus in Arlington — adjacent to Amazon HQ2, the Pentagon, and the Northern Virginia technology corridor — is one of the most strategically significant university campus expansions in America. The Innovation Campus is specifically designed to feed Amazon's HQ2 talent needs and the broader Northern Virginia technology and defense ecosystem. Students who complete part of their degree at the Innovation Campus gain access to Amazon, Bosch, and the dense defense contractor ecosystem of the DC suburbs while maintaining Virginia Tech credentials. The Virginia Tech Corporate Research Center — the technology and research park adjacent to main campus in Blacksburg — houses 200+ companies, creating a startup and industry partnership ecosystem that gives students applied research and entrepreneurship access without leaving campus.",

    institutionalSecret: "The Hokie Stone — the distinctive gray-green limestone quarried locally and used in virtually every building on campus — creates a physical coherence and a material identity that makes Virginia Tech's campus feel unlike any other. This is not incidental: the Hokie Stone is to Virginia Tech what the Yard is to Harvard — the physical expression of institutional identity. Hokie pride is earned through the campus itself, through the isolation of Blacksburg, and through the shared experience of Lane Stadium on football Saturdays. The April 16 Memorial — a permanent remembrance of the 2007 tragedy — is one of the most thoughtfully designed memorials on any American campus and reflects the resilience and community that defines Virginia Tech's identity.",

