    archetype: "The Aggie Nation — Loyalty, Service, Military Tradition, and the Most Cohesive Alumni Culture in American Higher Education",

    oneSentenceSummary: "Texas A&M is the university where loyalty is the curriculum — a 700,000-person Aggie network built on military tradition, Corps of Cadets culture, and a yell practice that happens at midnight before every home game, producing engineers, agriculturalists, business leaders, and military officers who hire each other with a ferocity that makes Texas A&M's alumni network one of the three most powerful referral cultures in American higher education.",

    pipeline: "62% acceptance rate overall; Engineering and Business programs more selective. #19 among public universities nationally (US News 2025). 57,000+ undergraduates on the main College Station campus — one of the largest enrollments in America. The Mays Business School is top-25 nationally. The College of Engineering is top-10 in petroleum, chemical, and industrial engineering. The College of Agriculture and Life Sciences is the largest agriculture program in the US by enrollment. ExxonMobil, Chevron, Schlumberger, Halliburton, and every major energy company maintain dedicated A&M recruiting pipelines. Lockheed Martin, Boeing, Raytheon, and every major defense contractor recruit the Corps of Cadets at volume. 700,000+ living alumni — one of the largest alumni networks in the world by absolute count.",

    hiddenPathway: "The Corps of Cadets is the largest military organization at any American university outside the service academies — 2,500+ cadets who participate in a military lifestyle while pursuing a full academic degree and earning a commission in any branch of the US military. Corps graduates enter the workforce with leadership experience, discipline, and a military alumni network that is disproportionately represented in energy company executive leadership, defense contracting, and government. The McFerrin Center for Entrepreneurship within Mays Business School is increasingly competitive with Texas and Rice for Austin and Houston startup ecosystem access. The Texas A&M AgriLife Research and Extension system — the largest state agricultural extension system in the US — creates applied research opportunities for agriculture and life sciences students that no other program at scale can match.",

    institutionalSecret: "The Aggie Network operates with a referral culture so intense and so specific that it has its own mythology: Aggies will stop what they are doing to help a fellow Aggie they have never met. The 'Howdy' culture — A&M's official greeting policy — is not a marketing affectation; it is a behavioral norm that permeates the campus and the alumni network. The Aggie Ring — distributed to students who complete 90 credit hours — is one of the most recognized college rings in America and functions as a professional signal in Texas business settings that immediately triggers the referral culture. Midnight Yell Practice — a 20,000-person gathering at Kyle Field the night before home football games — is the physical expression of an institutional loyalty that is genuinely unusual in American higher education.",

    theRoom: "College Station, Texas — a city of 120,000 built almost entirely around Texas A&M, 90 miles northwest of Houston and 100 miles northeast of Austin. The campus is one of the largest in the country: 5,200 acres, Kyle Field (102,000 capacity — one of the largest stadiums in the world), the George Bush Presidential Library, and the Century Tree as its most romantic landmark. The surrounding city is deeply Aggie-identified. Houston is close enough for internships and weekend access to one of the largest economic metros in America.",

    lifestyle: "Aggie culture is all-encompassing and by design. The traditions — Silver Taps, Muster, the 12th Man, Midnight Yell, the Aggie War Hymn — are maintained by students with an intentionality that reflects the understanding that tradition is the mechanism of belonging. The Corps is present but represents approximately 5% of the student body; the other 95% participate in Aggie culture through athletics, student organizations, and the social infrastructure. Greek life is present but secondary to Aggie-wide traditions.",

