    archetype: "The Southern Public Ivy — Journalism, Medicine, Business, and the Most Beloved College Town in the South",

    oneSentenceSummary: "UNC Chapel Hill is the oldest public university in America and the anchor of the Research Triangle — a top-5 public university whose Kenan-Flagler Business School, Hussman School of Journalism, and Gillings School of Public Health produce graduates embedded in a professional ecosystem stretching from Chapel Hill to Charlotte to Raleigh that is one of the fastest-growing in America.",

    pipeline: "17% acceptance rate overall; significantly more selective for out-of-state applicants. #5 among public universities nationally (US News 2025). 20,000 undergraduates. Kenan-Flagler Business School is top-20 nationally in finance, marketing, and real estate. The Hussman School of Journalism and Media is top-5 nationally. Gillings School of Global Public Health is top-3 nationally. Bank of America, Lowe's, VF Corporation, and the Charlotte banking corridor recruit UNC at volume. Goldman Sachs, McKinsey, and Deloitte all maintain Carolina recruiting pipelines. UNC School of Medicine is top-25. 340,000+ living alumni with extraordinary loyalty and concentration across the Southeast and Midwest.",

    hiddenPathway: "The Research Triangle — UNC, Duke, and NC State within 30 miles of each other — creates an intellectual and economic ecosystem unlike any other in the Southeast. Research Triangle Park (RTP), immediately between Chapel Hill and Raleigh, houses the US headquarters of IBM, Cisco, GlaxoSmithKline, Biogen, and 300+ other companies — and its 7,000 acres make it the largest research park in the United States. UNC students have direct access to RTP internships in pharmaceutical, technology, and data science roles that would require moving to Boston or San Francisco at peer institutions. The UNC Entrepreneurship Center, the Launch Chapel Hill accelerator, and the growing Durham startup ecosystem are creating a startup culture that is rapidly becoming one of the most active in the South.",

    institutionalSecret: "Franklin Street is not a side note — it is the social and cultural spine of the Chapel Hill undergraduate experience. The bars, restaurants, and community of Franklin Street create a college town culture that rivals Athens, Madison, and Austin in its intensity and warmth. The Carolina blue and the Dean Smith legacy in basketball organize the social and emotional life of the campus in a way that is more than athletics — it is a shared identity that graduates carry for decades. The Monday Gazebo and the Old Well as first-day-of-class rituals, the PIT as the social hub, and the Bell Tower as the graduation gathering point are traditions that create institutional belonging at a 20,000-student university.",

    theRoom: "Chapel Hill, North Carolina — a classic American college town of 60,000 built entirely around the university. The campus is beautiful: McCorkle Place, the Old Well, the Davie Poplar, and South Building anchor a physical environment of real architectural quality. Durham is 8 miles east — with the American Tobacco Campus, the Durham Bulls, and a growing arts and tech scene. Raleigh is 28 miles east. Charlotte is 165 miles southwest. The Research Triangle's combination of college-town intimacy and major research corridor access is unique in American higher education.",

    lifestyle: "ACC basketball culture defines the social calendar — Duke vs. Carolina is one of the most intense annual rivalries in American sports, and it is experienced by UNC students as a personal matter. Greek life is present but not dominant — approximately 20% participation. Franklin Street is the social center. The city of Durham has become increasingly important to the UNC social experience as it has transformed into one of the most dynamic mid-size cities in the South.",

    bestFitPersonality: "Journalism or business or public health career oriented, college town culture appreciative, ACC basketball identity resonant, Southeast or Midwest professional ambition, in-state Carolina or out-of-state high achiever, high Extraversion and Agreeableness",

