    oneSentenceSummary: "UC Santa Cruz is the UC campus that was designed to be different — residential colleges named after concepts rather than donors, a progressive academic culture, and a campus built inside a coastal redwood forest 32 miles from Silicon Valley that has somehow become one of the most important feeders to the technology industry in California.",

    pipeline: "47% acceptance rate for the Class of 2028. #27 among public universities nationally (US News 2025). 17,000 undergraduates. The Jack Baskin School of Engineering is a top-40 CS program with particular strength in computer game design, robotics, and computational biology — its proximity to Silicon Valley has created recruiting relationships with Apple, Google, and Monterey Bay area technology companies. The Institute for the Mathematics and Physics of the Universe at UCSC's Lick Observatory is one of the most significant astronomy and astrophysics research programs in the US. UC Santa Cruz is the managing organization for the W. M. Keck Observatory in Hawaii. The UCSC Science and Engineering Library is the most technically specialized library in the UC system. 75,000+ living alumni with significant Silicon Valley presence.",

    hiddenPathway: "UCSC's most undersurfaced career pipeline is its game design program — the Computer Science and Game Design BS is one of a small number of university programs in America that trains students in both the technical and creative dimensions of game development simultaneously. Santa Cruz graduates are recruited by EA, Riot Games, Blizzard, Activision, and the independent game development studios that cluster in the Bay Area. The Genomics Institute at UCSC is globally significant — the human genome browser (UCSC Genome Browser) was built here and is used by researchers worldwide, making UCSC the primary computational genomics resource for biomedical research globally. For students interested in computational biology, bioinformatics, or genomics, UCSC has a specific and unusual competitive advantage.",

    institutionalSecret: "The residential college system at UCSC is unlike any other in the UC system — ten colleges, each with its own academic focus, core course requirements, and character, spread across the forested campus. Cowell College (writing and humanities), Crown College (mathematics and science), Merrill College (social justice), Porter College (arts) — the college system creates genuine intellectual communities within a mid-size university. The forest campus is the most physically distinctive in the UC system: buildings built among coastal redwoods on a hillside above Monterey Bay, with deer wandering between classrooms and the Pacific visible from the upper campus.",

    theRoom: "Santa Cruz, California — a city of 65,000 on the northern end of Monterey Bay, 32 miles south of San Jose and 75 miles south of San Francisco. The UCSC campus is set on a forested hillside above the city — the Main Entrance Road winds through redwoods before opening onto the academic core. The Santa Cruz Beach Boardwalk, the surf culture of the Santa Cruz coast, and the progressive political culture of the city create a specific lifestyle context. Silicon Valley is 45 minutes north on Highway 17.",

    lifestyle: "Progressive, outdoors-oriented, and intellectually unconventional. UCSC's academic culture has historically valued depth of inquiry over professional preparation — the quarter system, the college structure, and the narrative evaluations (UCSC offered narrative transcripts instead of grades until 2001) reflect an institution that has always been more interested in how students think than what they can do. Greek life is minimal. Surf culture, hiking, and the Santa Cruz outdoor scene define the physical lifestyle. The proximity to Silicon Valley creates an increasing professional orientation that coexists with the campus's progressive identity.",

